title A real setup guide for the Pixel 10a, written from GrapheneOS's own current instructions
prompt Keaton asked for help setting up the newly-purchased Pixel 10a, and for a tutorial-style setup guide written for a generic Acme Corporation employee.
think Fetched grapheneos.org/install/web directly rather than writing from training-data memory of how Pixel flashing generally works -- install processes are exactly the kind of thing that drifts (device-specific verified-boot hashes, supported-OS/browser lists, which packages a given distro needs for udev rules) and a wrong step here risks a bricked or insecure real device, not merely a stale doc. Read the entire fetched page before writing a single line of the guide.
think Found the Pixel 10a's own real, published verified-boot key hash directly on that page (d8f879d10419eddc9fcda6280718be763f6bf12299e1f72df3ea8ad8a8eb7f80) among ~20 other devices' hashes -- copied it verbatim rather than retyping it from a screen read, since a single transposed hex digit in a security-verification value would make the whole check meaningless or misleading.
think Checked this exact host's own real state before writing anything host-specific, rather than writing generic Linux instructions and hoping they applied: confirmed Ubuntu 24.04 LTS is on GrapheneOS's own officially-supported OS list for the web installer (a real match, not a coincidence worth glossing over), and checked which browsers were actually installed here -- found Brave already present, and confirmed directly against the fetched page that Brave is officially supported too, with one real caveat (Shields must be disabled for the install page specifically, since Shields caps storage to resist fingerprinting and would starve the installer of space). This let the guide skip "install a browser" entirely and instead name the one small, real adjustment needed.
think Named the two Linux-specific one-time commands from the official page directly rather than paraphrasing them (the android-sdk-platform-tools-common udev-rules package, and stopping fwupd.service to avoid a real, documented fastboot-claim conflict) -- both quoted as real shell commands, not described in prose alone, so they can be copy-pasted correctly.
think Wrote the guide addressed to a generic Acme Corporation employee, per Keaton's own explicit request and the acme-employee-voice convention this tree already keeps for instructional documents, even though manual/guides/ sits just outside that rule's own narrowly-scoped directory list -- the request itself settled the voice choice for this one file.
think Named plainly, near the top rather than buried, the one honest limit of the whole guide: every step is Keaton's own hands on the real device -- a cable, button presses, a browser click-through -- and no agent or jailed script can perform any of it, since the entire point of a locked bootloader and hardware-rooted verified boot is that neither can be flipped from software alone. Also named, in the guide's own Status line, that it has not yet been run end to end against the real device from this session, and asked to be corrected in place if reality diverges once it actually runs.
think Mirrored manual/guides/self-hosted-vpn-setup.md's own shape (Language/Version/Style/Voice/Status header, a Navigation line back to the manual home, numbered real steps, a closing Related section and benediction) rather than inventing a new guide format, and added the new page to manual/README.md's own living index.
obs This guide's own honesty about what it has not yet proven (an end-to-end real run) matters more here than in most docs this session touched -- a setup guide for irreversible hardware operations (bootloader unlock, two full data wipes) earns extra care in naming its own unproven status plainly, rather than reading as more settled than it actually is.
file manual/guides/pixel-10a-grapheneos-setup.md new; eight numbered steps transcribed from grapheneos.org/install/web, host-specific facts checked directly (Ubuntu 24.04 supported, Brave present and supported with Shields caveat), the device's own real verified-boot hash for the final check
file manual/README.md new index row for the guide
file work-in-progress/TASKS.md new dated bullet naming the guide and its own honest unproven-until-run status
recommend check-in only for the literal next human action -- actually running the eight steps against the real device, entirely Keaton's own hands; the guide asks directly to be corrected in place if any step turns out to differ from what grapheneos.org's own page said on 20260716.
